revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-09 16:49:21.000000000', 'message': '[placement] Enable PUT dict to /allocations/{consumer_uuid}

In microversion 1.11 JSON schema is added to enable PUT to
/allocations/{consumer_uuid} using a dict-based format that is in the
same form as the response at GET /allocations/{consumer_uuid}. This is
considered good practice and also allows the PUT format to be composed
by resource provider uuid, which is useful.

Internally to handlers/allocation.py the same method (_set_allocations)
is used for every microversion. Any previous data structure is
transformed into the dict-ish form. This means that pre-existing tests
(like allocation-bad-class.yaml) continue to exercise the problems it
was made for, but needs to be pinned to an older microversion, rather than
being latest.

One issue revealed by this change that we may wish to address is that
while we require project_id and user_id on PUT they are not present in
the GET response. We can change this (as part of this microversion) if
we want but there are two (probably minor) concerns if we do:

* more complex sql query to join for the project and user info
* if we include that info in the representation, will people
  accidentally send back the _wrong_ project and user info because
  they fail to update it? by not including it, but requiring it, we
  force the caller to set it with the info they have

(Will update the change with the resolution of that issue.)

A subsequence patch will update the placement-api-ref, api history,
and provide a reno for this change.

Change-Id: Ib4b489f29da9571c1669a6eb50e0aa604ff87d6f
Implements: bp symmetric-allocations

commit_message:
[placement] Enable PUT dict to /allocations/{consumer_uuid}

Extend microversion 1.11 to add JSON schema to enable PUT to
/allocations/{consumer_uuid} using a dict-based format that is in the
same form as the response at GET /allocations/{consumer_uuid}. This is
considered good practice and also allows the PUT format to be composed
by resource provider uuid, which is useful.

Internally to handlers/allocation.py the same method (_set_allocations)
is used for every microversion. Any previous data structure is
transformed into the dict-ish form. This means that pre-existing tests
(like allocation-bad-class.yaml) continue to exercise the problems it
was made for, but needs to be pinned to an older microversion, rather than
being latest.

A subsequence patch will update the placement-api-ref, api history,
and provide a reno for this change.

Change-Id: Ib4b489f29da9571c1669a6eb50e0aa604ff87d6f
Implements: bp symmetric-allocations
Closes-Bug: #1708204

commit_message:
[placement] Include project_id and user_id in GET /allocations

In an new microversion, include project_id and user_id in the
output of GET /allocations/{consumer_uuid} so that subsequent
patches which will change the PUT representation (which requires
project_id and user_id) to be structured like the GET response
complete the realignment.

The microversion will be properly documented and reno'd when it
is fully complete, but is introduced in this patch.

Change-Id: Ie69ab746e98e6cf426af1fda34fcb7c127f1b296

commit_message:
Fix issues for post-allocations spec

Discussion after the merge of Ib4a3970a5d0e475c9b0a7fcb5f51e1ed3662befa
identified a few issues in the spec. This fixes those issues, for the
sake of future readers, and removes a body format that was not chosen.

Blueprint: post-allocations

commit_message:
let include-pypi-link imply release-type python-pypi

If the deliverable file says to include the PyPI link in release
emails, it's likely that it means the deliverable is published to PyPI
and should use those jobs.

Change-Id: I06b471c8992e75d315788463e75bd932503a928a
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
provide separate release types for server and non-server deliverables

Change the 'std' release type to 'python-server' and add a
'python-pypi' release type for deliverables that are published to
PyPI.

Separate the release job validation from the validation of release
version numbers and other settings to make the logic clearer.

Add a new function to determine the release type for a project, either
by checking the explicit value or guessing.

Update the unit tests that relied on 'std'.

Remove a unit test that tested a code path that has been removed.

Change-Id: I704ec75fec61ecb6ee379239a5fa8612cb01b426
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
[Micro version] Support description for instance

In Nova Compute API microversion 2.19, you can specify a “description”
attribute when creating, rebuilding, or updating a server instance. This
description can be retrieved by getting server details, or list details
for servers, this patch adds support for this attribute for instance in
horizon.

Change-Id: Ic9217234021d236aee8295915f1a9c3c544396b0
Implement-blueprint: support-description-for-instance

Use rngd to quickly fill up the entropy pool at boot time.

commit_message:
Switch from builtin shares to dynamic

Instead of a single hardcoded "share" allow shares to be
created after boot.

[{'created': '2017-10-10 20:16:19.000000000', 'message': 'Reduce MTU to work around neutron

With Neutron and VXLAN networking, large ethernet frames get
dropped, causing I/O problems. Reducing the MTU by 54 bytes
(the size of the VXLAN header) solves the problems.

Change-Id: I664be34659bc41f38c69d4b3e08120488cb07f83

Neutron.

commit_message:
Use DHCP for eth1 and enforce MTU

If there are 2 network interfaces, acquire DHCP leases from
both. Also fix the DHCP client script to accept the MTU from
Neutron.

Change-Id: I664be34659bc41f38c69d4b3e08120488cb07f83

commit_message:
Switch service projects to not publish to pypi

Some service projects were accidentally configured with
publish-to-pypi instead of release-openstack-server.
Switch this back. This tries to cover all milestone-driven
deliverables that never published to pypi in the past.

Change-Id: I50b1cfb3d892443cdb3faffe2f931914b0b47684

commit_message:
Use external mount programs instead of busybox

Avoid the busybox mount applets for NFS and CIFS because
the external mount apps are better.

Generally, we don't increase the requirements for bugfix-only releases. This patch literally means "ironic can no longer work with dracclient 1.3.0", which does not seem to be strictly the case.'}, {'account_id': 23847, 'date': '2017-10-01 20:45:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

> Generally, we don't increase the requirements for bugfix-only
 > releases. This patch literally means "ironic can no longer work
 > with dracclient 1.3.0", which does not seem to be strictly the
 > case.

We have found that the Dell ironic 3d party CI's testing of proposed changes against Dell PowerEdge 12G and 13G servers fails much more often than it does against 14G servers. That specifically applies to the tests against the ironic classic pxe_drac driver. Only that driver implements the Lifecycle Controller best practice to ensure that the iDRAC is ready before interacting with the iDRAC. The root cause of the failures is that the timeout is too short. In our testing, increasing it alleviates the false negative 12G and 13G failures.

Additionally, we found that our downstream solution consistently fails to deploy when 12G and 13G servers are in the cluster.

Please note that 13G continues to be supported.

To my mind, the above demonstrates that "ironic can no longer work with dracclient 1.3.0".

I continue to give this change a Code-Review -1, because of my questions and suggestions about the release note.'}, {'account_id': 10250, 'date': '2017-10-03 18:53:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(3 comments)

I disagree on renaming the file.  This patch does not fix a bug.  It upgrades the version of the library that ironic uses, and the name of the file clearly reflects that.'}, {'account_id': 10250, 'date': '2017-10-03 18:56:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

The iDRAC driver CI uses a mix of 12G and 13G hardware, and we are planning on adding 14G to it as well.  We've found that the prior is-ready timeout is not sufficient for 12G hardware, and that 13G hardware frequently times out because the timeout is not long enough.  The intent of this patch is to help stabilize the iDRAC driver CI by switching to a version of python-dracclient that has a longer is-ready timeout value."}, {'account_id': 10250, 'date': '2017-10-03 18:56:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 14629, 'date': '2017-10-03 19:06:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

[{'created': '2017-09-27 17:57:24.000000000', 'message': 'python-dracclient driver version update

This patch moves to the 1.3.1 version of python-dracclient to help stabilize
the iDRAC CI.  It was found that the check to determine if the iDRAC is ready
frequently timed out on 12G and 13G hardware because the timeout value was too
short.  The 1.3.1 version of python-dracclient increases the timeout value so
incorrect timeouts will no longer occur on 12G and 13G hardware.

Change-Id: I8f08909867a523611e3b646973cfc513e1b66571
Closes-Bug: #1719965

commit_message:
python-dracclient driver version update

This patch moves to the 1.3.1 version of python-dracclient to help
stabilize the iDRAC CI.  It was found that the check to determine if
the iDRAC is ready frequently timed out on 12G and 13G hardware because
the timeout value was too short.  The 1.3.1 version of
python-dracclient increases the timeout value so incorrect timeouts
will no longer occur on 12G and 13G hardware.

Change-Id: I8f08909867a523611e3b646973cfc513e1b66571
Closes-Bug: #1719965
Depends-On: I9dc476d3c28475919404077875f04fd006d4464a

commit_message:
Always call iptables-restore with -w if done once

In the case where we called iptables-restore with a
-w argument and it succeeded, we should short-circuit
future calls to always use -w, instead of trying
without it, just to fall-back to using it on failure.

While analyzing some l3-agent log files I have seen
lots of "Perhaps you want to use the -w option?",
followed by a call with -w, followed by not using it
the next time. Changing this can save one failing
call to iptables-restore.

Change-Id: Icac99eb1d43648c64b6beaee0d6201f990eacb51
Related-bug: #1712185

commit_message:
Revert unnecessary wrap line change in stable backport

A stable backport commit b31de0092890c443d5bd3efceaa8081ab25f2f4e
introduces a string change only with a wrapping line position.
It is unnecessary and it loses existing translation unnecessarily [1].

I am not sure we can recover a corresponding translation in Zanata
automatically but I think it is worth trying it.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/509501/4

Change-Id: I727c56b64da05fe4346eb0642d4754b935054351

[{'created': '2017-10-25 19:19:17.000000000', 'message': 'Hide instance actions that are forbidden due to lock

This patch prevents instance actions which are forbidden during the time an
instance is locked.

The actions affected are:

- Delete
- Start and stop
- Reboot
- Rebuild
- Resize, revert and confirm resize
- Shelve, unshelve
- Pause, unpause, suspend, resume
- Attach and detach volume
- Attach and detach interface
- Update instance metadata
- Live migrate

This list of actions covers all instance actions that are currently
implemented in Horizon, which the Nova API does not allow to be performed
during an instance lock.

Ref.: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/api.py

Closes-Bug: #1573566
'}]
commit_message:
Hide instance actions that are forbidden due to lock

This patch prevents instance actions which are forbidden during the time an
instance is locked.

The actions affected are:

- Delete
- Start and stop
- Reboot
- Rebuild
- Resize, revert and confirm resize
- Shelve, unshelve
- Pause, unpause, suspend, resume
- Attach and detach volume
- Attach and detach interface
- Update instance metadata
- Live migrate

This list of actions covers all instance actions that are currently
implemented in Horizon, which the Nova API does not allow to be performed
during an instance lock.

Ref.: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/api.py

Change-Id: Icb1d290cdd2b26891338c490998eaf8d5fbb9c84
Closes-Bug: #1573566

subject: Remove unified queue from gate pipeline
messages: [{'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2017-10-23 10:27:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 17068, 'date': '2017-10-23 13:12:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 22582, 'date': '2017-10-26 09:23:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 23163, 'date': '2017-10-26 14:40:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-23 10:27:32.000000000', 'message': "Remove unified queue from gate pipeline

Initially the intent for adding this was to better test
any patches for roles together before they merge, but it
has had the unintended side-effect of causing patches to
take much longer to merge (because they all get lined up
in a single queue, rather than independent queues) and
a lot more infra resources are used (because a patch
that fails at the top of the queue will result in all
subsequent patches restarting all their tests).

As discussed in the channel, we'd prefer to revert back
to the previous independent queue method of testing. It
has served us well.

Change-Id: I7e62c9f5904e7a56700e8892993be266fbccc9dd
"}]
commit_message:
Remove unified queue from gate pipeline

Initially the intent for adding this was to better test
any patches for roles together before they merge, but it
has had the unintended side-effect of causing patches to
take much longer to merge (because they all get lined up
in a single queue, rather than independent queues) and
a lot more infra resources are used (because a patch
that fails at the top of the queue will result in all
subsequent patches restarting all their tests).

As discussed in the channel, we'd prefer to revert back
to the previous independent queue method of testing. It
has served us well.

Change-Id: I7e62c9f5904e7a56700e8892993be266fbccc9dd

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-09-20 20:03:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

There are a lot of tests that don't require project_id and user_id and all enforcement of that requirement is at the HTTP API level.

Dan has expressed a reasonable wish that the object and database enforce that requirement, including having a blocker migration that makes sure it is true for existing allocations.

I'm kind of the opinion we should continue to let the HTTP API enforce things and let the db and the object fields be optional, simply because it is the smaller change and requires no migration.

I'm happy to proceed with Dan's plan but I've run out of mojo to get started on it now, so there's time for other people to weigh in if they have opinions."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-09-20 22:34:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Oh, also, totally forgot this one: We have to continue to be able to not have  project_id and user_id in allocations because of microversions.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-09-20 23:56:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-09-21 00:01:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Workflow-1

This new version loads project_id and user_id from the db, if they are set. It does not enforce that those must be non-null because of microversions on the api.

-W because:

* is project_id or user_id are set, then the other must be, we should enforce that
* there are some missing test cases related to capacity checking. In PS8 there was an ordering problem between deleting allocations and checking capacity which would have been found if the right test cases were around
* probably still some lose ends from the discussion on ps8 that still need to be resolved'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-09-21 00:06:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

[{'created': '2017-09-04 00:31:07.000000000', 'message': "Move project_id and user_id to Allocation object

It had been on the AllocationList object but this make it impossible to
have a an AllocationList from multiple project ids, something we want to
be able to do with the new use of migration uuids.

In later patches this will also be used to demonstrate correction of an
issue with consumer ids not being properly associated with project ids.

In the proces of making this change the obj_make_compatible in the
Allocation class was removed. We don't do RPC. We don't need this and
the choice in this change was either to add more compatibility changes
or simply get rid of the routine. Leaving it as is would be misleading.

Change-Id: I3cf887bd541c187ec3baca2ae3f8c16f1754e96e

commit_message:
Move project_id and user_id to Allocation object

It had been on the AllocationList object but this makes it impossible to
have an AllocationList from multiple project ids. When it was decided to
allow setting allocations from multiple different consumers, it was
decided that since we were already in the code changing things, we
should also make adjustments to allow each allocation to have its own
project and user id.

In the process, ensure that if a persisted Allocation has a project_id
and user_id associated with it, load those values when the Allocation is
loaded (either list allocations by consumer or by resource provider).

We cannot enforce (at the object level) that Allocations must have a
project_id and user_id because there is a microversion where they are
not required that we continue to support. In newer microversions the
JSON schema enforces the their requirement.

Inspecting the placement fixtures related to this change revealed a bug
with a missing user_id in one Allocation being created.

Change-Id: I3cf887bd541c187ec3baca2ae3f8c16f1754e96e

'}, {'created': '2017-09-22 16:19:23.000000000', 'message': "Defer exceptions in calculating node_data()

When generating the node_data() for a resource, catch and store any
exceptions (other than InvalidTemplateAttribute) encountered while
getting attributes. Re-raise the exception at the point where we try to
read the attribute value, including where we try to serialise the
NodeData object to store in the database.

In convergence, we generate and immediately serialise the NodeData, so
this should result in no substantial change in behaviour there.

In other situations (e.g. when we're just loading the data to show the
stack), this prevents an error in attribute calculation from aborting
the whole operation. The exception will still be raised if (and only if)
the erroneous attribute is accessed, but may be handled more
appropriately. For example, errors in calculating output values are
handled by reporting an error only for that particular output.

Closes-Bug: #1712280

commit_message:
Defer exceptions in calculating node_data()

When generating the node_data() for a resource, catch and store any
exceptions (other than InvalidTemplateAttribute) encountered while
getting attributes. Re-raise the exception at the point where we try to
read the attribute value, including where we try to serialise the
NodeData object to store in the database.

In convergence, we generate and immediately serialise the NodeData, so
this should result in no substantial change in behaviour there.

In other situations (e.g. when we're just loading the data to show the
stack), this prevents an error in attribute calculation from aborting
the whole operation. The exception will still be raised if (and only if)
the erroneous attribute is accessed, but may be handled more
appropriately. For example, errors in calculating output values are
handled by reporting an error only for that particular output.

Change-Id: Idc97aee87405cc13e83be3373078b52e725850ea
Co-Authored-By: Zane Bitter <zbitter@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1712280

commit_message:
[swarm-fedora-atomic] fix cluster etcd_lb protocol definition

In file drivers/swarm_fedora_atomic_v1/templates/cluster.yaml,
etcd_lb protocol is hardcoded:

  etcd_lb:
    type: ../../common/templates/lb.yaml
    properties:
      fixed_subnet: {get_attr: [network, fixed_subnet]}
      external_network: {get_param: external_network}
      protocol: HTTP
      port: 2379

but protocol should be: {get_param: loadbalancing_protocol}

Change-Id: Ib36ff0a99e219db9c0e0f35267faf317f5a14554
Closes-Bug: #1712054

commit_message:
Swarm: Incorrect reference to Flannel variables

Swarm network-config-service makes reference to
wrong variables:
- FLANNEL_ETCD instead of FLANNEL_ETCD_ENDPOINTS
- FLANNEL_ETCD_KEY instead of FLANNEL_ETCD_PREFIX

Change-Id: Ie9f1913177f4a5fd803bcf8de1de66384395ecdd
Closes-Bug: #1679301

commit_message:
Remove rsync from xinetd when upgrading to containerized deployment

The rsync service needs to be removed from the xinetd service, otherwise
the swift_rsync container will permanently restart because the rsync
port (873) is still in use after upgrading.

Closes-Bug: 1718403
Change-Id: I283919891d00731c96ef963b0c4137d10144ccaf

[{'created': '2017-10-25 07:13:30.000000000', 'message': "VGPU: Account for flavors supporting VGPUs

We previously only accepted flavors having extraspecs only supporting
to call a custom resource class or overriding an existing resource class
in the flavor (ie. VCPU, MEMORY_MB and DISK_GB only). Now we would like
to ask for VGPUs but since it's neither a custom resource class nor a
flavor resource class, we need to make sure we can accept additional
existing resource classes that aren't in the flavor.

Partially Implements: blueprint add-support-for-vgpu
Co-Authored-By: naichuans <naichuan.sun@citrix.com>

Change-Id: I84ea7779b196ec535f4109c5343c8de9056a2b2d

commit_message:
Accept all standard resource classes in flavor extra specs

When transforming flavor resources into resource classes, we look at any
'resources' extraspec key to know which resource classes to ask.
That said, we were previously only accepting custom resource classes or
existing standard resource classes if and only if they were in the flavor
(and then overriding them).
Given operators would want to ask for specific resource classes (like VGPU)
that are not flavor fields, we need to modify the utils method to make sure
we accept them.

Partially Implements: blueprint add-support-for-vgpu
Co-Authored-By: Huan Xie <huan.xie@citrix.com>

Change-Id: I84ea7779b196ec535f4109c5343c8de9056a2b2d

commit_message:
[Urgent] fix tap_enabled for sfc

1. What is the problem
A new change Icd4bf90d54f4edb443467b192e4e639fde749d4e is merged in
networking-sfc, making unit tests fail.

2. What is the solution for the problem
Add an attribute "tap_enabled" for PortPairGroup in the unit tests
for sfc, and set it as False.

3. What features need to be implemented to the Tricircle to
realize the solution
N/A.

Change-Id: I0e92117be9a2beed809538412832c6a884fa1b55

commit_message:
Fix issue creating NGT using dashboard

Since Django 1.10 a new property DATA_UPLOAD_MAX_NUMBER_FIELDS causes some
plugins to fail during NGT creation. This patch adds a file to override
this property for sahara dashboard.

Depends-On: Id4d15b8bd5f032ff457395af5d77b255b6077a2a
Change-Id: I29ec88d7c733d4a977867dc24e13eb8e98fbcc48
Closes-bug: #1714575
Co-Authored-By: ArchiFleKs <lefevre.kevin@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 841f0a26f423139a0871241884c508f8736cc7f0)

commit_message:
Ignore I202 in pep8 (flake8), skip Testodll3

This is a new check added which is breaking the gate. Igrnoing it for now.
If someone really loves messing with import order, feel free to fix it.

Also some change in neutron is breaking Testodll3 so skipping it because
we're deprecating V1 drivers this cycle.
If anyone cares about the V1 L3 driver before it's in the trashcan of
history, feel free to fix the test.

Change-Id: I99bad4ea73ed30f77f8e3773b616279f194ba680

commit_message:
Remove references to Big Tent from project list slides

This commit removes the references to the Big Tent from the project list
slides. We're trying to move away from that term because it causes
confusion to a lot of people. Instead we should call them OpenStack
projects. One note about big tent is left in, because people still use
the term, but we should use that to explain it's the old way to describe
all OpenStack projects.

Change-Id: Ifea66e1dae9c4e644e3efa70c0be0526b24d41cc

commit_message:
Move log collection to 'post' stage

To ensure that logs are collected regardless of whether
a job succeeds, fails or times out, we move the log
collection to the 'post' stage of the job definition.

As the job playbook only gets run in nodepool, we remove
the detection of nodepool in the log collection script
and also remove the trap which executes it so that it
is only ever run when executed in zuul.

Change-Id: I5ab31cc141804cbcb6d8721032a79d0c724fc0a2

@Sharat,

To address @Tom's comment, you can perform the following steps:

1. Generate a migration file
$ magnum-db-manage revision -m "rename external network id in baymodel"

2. The command above should create a file in folder 'magnum/db/sqlalchemy/alembic/versions/'. Edit that file to alter the column name from 'external_network_id' to 'external_network'.

3. Migrate the DB:
$ magnum-db-manage upgrade

4. Restart magnum-api and magnum-cond and test the changes.

5. Rerun the unit tests to make sure it passes.
$ tox -epy27
$ tox -epep8'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2016-06-29 19:10:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Vendor in the RDO GPG keys to install

This way we avoid all networking failures.

Copy RPM keys into correct place

This patch copies the RPM keys into /etc/pki/rpm-gpg/ and
maintains their original names. This should allow the LXC
cache process to copy over the keys.

Combined backport of:
- https://review.openstack.org/515101
- https://review.openstack.org/515206

Change-Id: If95de543d2a2a7ad22435900e7923fc942cdd297

commit_message:
Handle exception on adding secgroup

If user adds security group to an instance and the instance already
has that security group, neutron will return a 400 response. Nova
should handle the 400 response properly. In before, Nova doesn't
seem to handle this case and end-user gets a 500 response. This
commit fixed it.

Closes-Bug: #1691274
Change-Id: I58b19ef6b537d690df90e542b6af3c64773ecc87

commit_message:
Ensure dst subfolder exists in post build jobs

We ensure that parent directory exists while trying to sync into
subdir, as result post job failed.
This patch ensures we created subdirectory where we will sync files
before sync.

Change-Id: I85ad8d6d719d0115c869a11cac3233ef203de1be
Closes-Bug: #1727652

commit_message:
Fix mistakes in tempest playbook

There were two mistakes in tempest playbook causing LBaaS v2 and Octavia
jobs to fail:

* if clause in bash requires usage of [ ] syntax to get the comparisons
  to work.
* $PROJECTS additions cannot be defined in local.conf.

This commit fixes both.

Change-Id: I7eda3b5e263565b8845ffeaa480f406a3a3f0731
Closes-Bug: 1727668

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-24 22:09:14.000000000', 'message': "SUSE: Improve openSUSE repositories handling

It's somewhat risky to assume that the host already has the default
repositories named as 'repo-oss' and 'repo-update'. In practise, these
repos could be named anything. If we install the same repo twice because
the filename differs, then strange things might happen. It's cheap and
doesn't cause too much overhead to actually wipe all the repositories
that come with the default LXC container and re-create them in a
predicatable way.

Change-Id: Ib267ba84d4ff3e4661ec186dcce3cfcc54895f0c
"}, {'created': '2017-10-25 08:06:40.000000000', 'message': "SUSE: Improve openSUSE repositories handling

commit_message:
SUSE: Improve openSUSE repositories handling

It's somewhat risky to assume that the host already has the default
repository files named as 'repo-oss' and 'repo-update'. In practise, these
repos could be named anything. If we install the same repo twice because
the filename differs, then strange things might happen. Lets just use
the zypper output to find out if the repos we care about are really
there. We also clean the metadata at the end and we start fresh.

Change-Id: Ib267ba84d4ff3e4661ec186dcce3cfcc54895f0c

commit_message:
update cinder kmgr parameter for Queens

puppet-cinder deprecated keymgr_api_class in favor of keymgr_backend to
reflect what Cinder team did in Queens.
Also, puppet-cinder will default the correct backend from now, so no
need to override it here.

Depends-On: I6f015a4ed4980d37622bb2931477af916cfc9003
Related-Bug: #1725298
Change-Id: I0da30ecfc1c7c419e2554eec20aed1825e62df5a

commit_message:
Disable voting on 2 multinode tripleo jobs

scenario001 and 004 are timeouting too much when deploying with
containers.
We're investigating why but in the meantime let's disable voting for
now.

Change-Id: I35d1cb886ae17c4bd4623d37a057fb670cd25bfe

commit_message:
Convert the AIO from using overlayfs to machinectl

The LXC container create role now supports using machinectl for
container storaeg. This change updates the default AIO bootstrap
role to leverage the new capabilities.

Change-Id: Icb1745fbd5b7d0c866b5dce1def1b13312da3612
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Add new repo for Neutron L2GW Tempest Plugin

This imports from a temporary github repo that preserves the history of
the plugin and additionally applies the openstack cookiecutter to it.

commit_message:
Translate NotFound to InvalidTemplateAttribute

In 48fcaf3fb218617512b1ea1f62a83f0839d70856 we changed the exception raised
in grouputils.get_resource() from InvalidTemplateAttribute to NotFound.
This was appropriate, but when get_resource() is called from
grouputils.get_nested_attrs() then we need to translate the exception to
InvalidTemplateAttribute for the attribute calculation code to handle it
appropriately.

Change-Id: Ic66b652b3a468d02b01cff2818b5e3814abc734a
Related-Bug: #1723315

commit_message:
Fix AttributeError in BlockDeviceMapping.obj_load_attr

The BDM has no uuid attribute so the debug message in here
would result in an AttributeError. This has been around since
the creation of this object, and the debug log message was
probably copied from the Instance object.

This was only exposed in Pike when this code started
lazy-loading the instance field:

  I1dc54a38f02bb48921bcbc4c2fdcc2c946e783c1

So this change fixes that bug and adds tests for obj_load_attr.

Change-Id: I8b55227b1530a76c2f396c035384abd89237d936
Closes-Bug: #1726871

commit_message:
Vendor in the RDO GPG keys to install

This way we avoid all networking failures.

Copy RPM keys into correct place

This patch copies the RPM keys into /etc/pki/rpm-gpg/ and
maintains their original names. This should allow the LXC
cache process to copy over the keys.

Combined backport of:
- https://review.openstack.org/515103
- https://review.openstack.org/515208

Change-Id: I07b04301629e3b2a176c210ed7989f8d699b7e8c

commit_message:
Kubespray installation via config download mechanism

Add external_deploy_tasks for Kubespray installation. This makes
Kubespray installation work with the config download mechanism.

If the undercloud doesn't already contain /usr/share/kubespray
directory, it will be git-cloned. This is to bridge a gap before we
figure out where we get Kubespray RPM from.

Co-Authored-By: Flavio Percoco <flaper87@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I2573261bfd3d63aff1310b80fc454becc7504437

commit_message:
Add legacy tempest troveclient job

Add a job to for the tempest tests on python-troveclient. This
job existed in Zuul v2 / Jenkins and the job definitions is
necessary to enable the Trove devstack plugin.

Change-Id: I4d2b0766c97b99fa30bc51989424a25313ff2e45

commit_message:
Use infra proxy server for trunk.r.o in delorean-deps

RDO is moving dependencies repo to trunk.rdoproject.org for
master repos as part of a dependencies improvement effort.

This patch replaces trunk.rdoproject.org by the local proxy
in the delorean-deps.repo.

commit_message:
Copy RPM keys into correct place

This patch copies the RPM keys into /etc/pki/rpm-gpg/ and
maintains their original names. This should allow the LXC
cache process to copy over the keys.

Depends-On: Icfd7e2b110541f85bf98efc384a9698dbbbd9682
Change-Id: I8acf7237c1bcbf7dc98d08aa5907972b69574bba

commit_message:
Remove wrapping of database exceptions in _get_collection()

* Method _get_collection() in api.py wraps all DB exceptions with
  DBQueryEntryError. It causes a problem because if it raises a
  DBDeadlock exception then it's not handled by @retry_on_deadlock
  decorator and the corresponding workflow operation gets lost.
  This patch remove this wrapping and also the exception class
  because it's not used anywhere else.

Closes-Bug: #1727152

Change-Id: If885bb63dc165aaf19001a4ff2c381732ee38982
(cherry picked from commit 49e2a53a9aaaef7e5b311716742cef69a2a49326)

commit_message:
apply language-specific version rules more carefully

Sometimes we have repos that look like puppet or nodejs projects when
they aren't. If an explicit release-type is given, use that instead of
guessing before applying the version rules.

Change-Id: I4cee33ef8da68e02d4f009e22d4c2480cb94384d
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

No logs - something's wrong here. In fact there are less logs than before.

FYI mordred mentioned earlier, referring to http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs/tree/zuul.d/jobs.yaml#n200

Many of the job types (like in this case the tox job) take an argument of "zuul_work_dir" which tells it which directory to operate in - that variable tends to default to 'zuul.project.src_dir' - which is the src dir of the project that triggered the job.

commit_message:
[DNM]zuul.d: run.yml: Use new BUILD_DIR variable for log collection

zuulv3 changed the way logs are collected. Logs are expected to be in
zuul.executor.work_root/logs. We can't set our existing WORKING_DIR
variable to that location since we expect it to be set to the root of
the cloned directory. As such, we create a new BUILD_DIR variable
to control where the logs will be stored.

Change-Id: I0a1ea9b25a6753b982cb33dd8ac2ef476c2e1f25

commit_message:
Copy RPM keys into correct place

This patch copies the RPM keys into /etc/pki/rpm-gpg/ and
maintains their original names. This should allow the LXC
cache process to copy over the keys.

Change-Id: Icfd7e2b110541f85bf98efc384a9698dbbbd9682

Also, minor typo at the commit msg header (Support searching...)"}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2017-10-09 07:08:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2017-10-10 14:59:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

> Why if both MAC and IP are specified, the search targets to find
 > only one of those parameters? Shouldn't the search fit both? In my
 > opinion, if the user specifies both MAC and IP for the desired
 > port, the port to search should have both fields as requested (in
 > the same way as you are creating the port with the provided MAC and
 > IP if not existing)

commit_message:
Support searching existing port with macaddress

Kuryr currently supports running container with existing neutron
port with matched IP address(es). This patch adds support for
searching existing neutron port with matching MAC address as
alternative.

End-users have two options to pass existing neutron port to kuryr:
* Use --ip and/or --ip6 to specify the IP address(es) of the
  existing neutron port
* Use --mac-address to specify the MAC address of the existing port.

If both IP and MAC address are specified, kuryr will search with IP
first, then search with MAC. If both searches are missed, kuryr
will create a new port with the specified IP and MAC address.

Implements: blueprint existing-port-by-mac
Change-Id: I1bca7d25aa951d218e579e160a4f18b00b7c14f6

commit_message:
chown fernet keys to match container's keystone user and group

We used to use the host's keystone user and group. This is wrong since
we need to use the container's keystone user and group, which differs
from the host. This fixes that.

Change-Id: I0a64843c94bb173bb9e418bfca26927c1e2a123f
Closes-Bug: #1726727

commit_message:
Enable Python hash randomization for tests

This should be enabled for all tests to ensure
we don't introduce bugs related to code relying
on ordering of unordered types.

Change-Id: I7150e6f222c8b7a264da2d497ea879028ab24b12

commit_message:
Add verify for datastore of replica to make sure consist with master

According bug description, when create a replica should validate
that slave datastore and version matching with master datastore and version.
To solve this problem,I only added judgement for datastore version id when create a replica,
because the same datastore version id must be the same datastore type.
Also provide a test case to validate the method.

Change-Id: Ie3c7cb1a134910aa137352ce3380301d543708a4
Closes-Bug: #1357709

commit_message:

It seems ceilometer api has been removed[1].

As part od zuulv3 transition we are moving jobs to project repo[2]
and change to enable gnocchi devstack plugin at the gate has to wait
till the movement is complete.

We probably have no other option but to disable the test for the
time being.

commit_message:
log the output of list-changes to a separate file for easier reading

Having the rather complex output of list-changes mixed in with the
main job log can make it difficult to read. Continue to include the
data in the main log file but also write it to a separate file that is
easier to consume.

Change-Id: If4d3b56c76b2bf513b2d44ffedf5825f562f4bfb
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-08-16 13:02:20.000000000', 'message': "Don't read config in cred_factory module

The credentials_factory module loads a few bit configuration
at module import time when the DEFAULT_PARAMS variable is defined.
This is not a good idea as it forces configuration to be loaded
even during test discovery. Besides DEFAULT_PARAMS was out of
date as it did not include http_timeout.

Replacing the DEFAULT_PARAMS variable with calls to
config.service_client_config().

Not loading CONF at test discovery time uncovered the fact that
the account generator unit tests were depending on oslo log
configuration parameters to be there. Mocking the log setup
step fixed the issue.

Change-Id: I6e0eb85b3749baedb6035f59ed1c66850f6c95fb

commit_message:
Don't read config in cred_factory module

The credentials_factory module loads a few bit configuration
at module import time when the DEFAULT_PARAMS variable is defined.
This is not a good idea as it forces configuration to be loaded
even during test discovery. Besides DEFAULT_PARAMS was out of
date as it did not include http_timeout.

Replacing the DEFAULT_PARAMS variable with calls to
config.service_client_config().

Not loading CONF at test discovery time uncovered the fact that
the account generator unit tests were depending on oslo log
configuration parameters to be there. Mocking the log setup
step fixed the issue.

Change-Id: I6e0eb85b3749baedb6035f59ed1c66850f6c95fb

commit_message:
Fix prechecks fail with docker not in deployment host

This changes only evaluates baremetal host group
to look for docker versions.

Change-Id: I64a7314b332958d003f88a00aa73ba79a760a051
Closes-Bug: #1700986
(cherry picked from commit 3b7ab63a19b4836e399a422e153770425e88d2d7)

commit_message:
Match job-output as console logs for getthelogs

New Zuul jobs produce the job-output log, which needs to
be fetched by the script. The console.htm[l] is not used
anymore.

Change-Id: Ibd65f0a7e6503ac54c3cb6f5d65ba1e5ef7ed89a
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobreli@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Switch vbmc to Systemd's instantiated services and open up corresponding firewall

We currently use the following single systemd service to start all vbmc
instances:

  Type=oneshot
  ExecStart=/bin/bash -c 'for bmc in $(ls /root/.vbmc/); do vbmc start $bmc; done'
  ExecStop=/bin/bash -c 'for bmc in $(ls /root/.vbmc/); do vbmc stop $bmc; done'

While this works okay for deployment and undercloud reboot, it does
not restart a crashing vbmc process. Let's switch to starting a vbmc process
via systemd's instantiated service, which will cover for all existing
cases and can also take care of restarting a crashing vbmc process:

$ systemctl status virtualbmc@ceph_2
  virtualbmc@ceph_2.service - VirtualBMC ceph_2 service
   Loaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/virtualbmc@.service; disabled; vendor preset: disabled)
   Active: active (running) since Sun 2017-10-08 07:09:36 UTC; 23s ago
  Process: 18184 ExecStart=/bin/vbmc start %i (code=exited, status=0/SUCCESS)
 Main PID: 18194 (vbmc)
   CGroup: /system.slice/system-virtualbmc.slice/virtualbmc@ceph_2.service
           18194 /usr/bin/python2 /bin/vbmc start ceph_2

Oct 08 07:09:35 undercloud systemd[1]: Starting VirtualBMC ceph_2 service...
Oct 08 07:09:36 undercloud systemd[1]: PID file /root/.vbmc/ceph_2/pid not readable (yet?) after start.
Oct 08 07:09:36 undercloud systemd[1]: Started VirtualBMC ceph_2 service.

$ kill 18194
$ systemctl status virtualbmc@ceph_2
  virtualbmc@ceph_2.service - VirtualBMC ceph_2 service
   Loaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/virtualbmc@.service; disabled; vendor preset: disabled)
   Active: active (running) since Sun 2017-10-08 07:10:22 UTC; 816ms ago
  Process: 18311 ExecStop=/bin/vbmc stop %i (code=exited, status=0/SUCCESS)
  Process: 18319 ExecStart=/bin/vbmc start %i (code=exited, status=0/SUCCESS)
 Main PID: 18328 (vbmc)
   CGroup: /system.slice/system-virtualbmc.slice/virtualbmc@ceph_2.service
           18328 /usr/bin/python2 /bin/vbmc start ceph_2

Oct 08 07:10:22 undercloud systemd[1]: virtualbmc@ceph_2.service holdoff time over, scheduling restart.
Oct 08 07:10:22 undercloud systemd[1]: Starting VirtualBMC ceph_2 service...
Oct 08 07:10:22 undercloud systemd[1]: PID file /root/.vbmc/ceph_2/pid not readable (yet?) after start.
Oct 08 07:10:22 undercloud systemd[1]: Started VirtualBMC ceph_2 service.

Additionally let's open the IPMI ports used by vbmc on the undercloud.
This way ironic on the overcloud and cluster stonith can actually work
correctly.

Change-Id: I2d2f8554a58196e88996aee5089899529b5af831
Closes-Bug: #1722037

Mirror images from RDO server

Mirror promoted images from RDO server to RH1 cloud
Rename all ipa_images.tar to ironic-python-agent.tar
Remove old promotion code from mirror-server

This review adds checks for network_isolation to be true before
including network_isolation_args, which will not be defined
for deploys without network isolation.

commit_message:
Set empty default for network_isolation_args

When the deployment does not include network isolation,
network_isolation_args needs to default to "".

Change-Id: Ie3fadbc104c18e159ab8d3f0eec37a360d70cc70

commit_message:
use a non-default virthost_user for the basic test

our ci tests were masking a number of problems because our virthost
and undercloud were using the same username (so /home/stack was a
valid path on both hosts).  this change modifies ci-scripts/basic.sh
to use a non-default virthost_user.

Change-Id: I69565d0f5268a6d53cfe9c7e78283b9ad799941c

But it's known that in_ works faster [1], especially when filtering

commit_message:
Replace or_ with in_ function for searching queries

Now in several queries we use or_ to define filter conditions.
But it's known that in_ works faster [1], especially when filtering
occurs on non-indexed fields. Therefore it's suggested to replace
or_ with in_.

Local tests showed that the performance for such requests increases
to 30%, depending on the size of the database.

[1] https://stackoverflow.com/questions/782915/mysql-or-vs-in-performance

Change-Id: I47caf99b9b1a66713f9d92bca0d5f692b7f2a717
(cherry picked from commit 2c1aa097b737262fa95b35a02774d88030ed61ec)

commit_message:
Follow up for symlink implementaion

This attempts to resolve:

- Fix SymlinkObjectContext and SymlinkContainerContext to be consistent
  with parent (and other child) WSGIContext framework

- Refactor handle_get_head to be recursive style and it will be intuitive
  for success case and error cases

- Catch HTTPException on top-level call in the middleware. Otherwise, the
  raised Exception can be caught on another middleware

- Change symlink put length check as content_length rather than trying to
  read 1 byte

- Other various minor nits

Change-Id: Iaf18b83760ef65d861167bdffa0ef6ed105bb54d

commit_message:
RedHat: Export rpm gpg keys to /etc/pki/rpm-gpg/ subdirectory

We should export the keys to the proper /etc/pki/rpm-gpg subdirectory so
we can easily share them with the LXC containers template. That
directory is already shared with the containers which means that our
keys will find their way to the containers automatically.

Change-Id: I030d60d7048314393d1141be9e73e0660717025c

Use the new containers tag name for master and pike

The container promotion started to use "current-tripleo" instead of
"passed-ci", point our upstream jobs to the proper ones.

commit_message:
Use addClassResourceCleanup in network's resource_cleanup

This is to:
1. Stop using resource_cleanup in network's base, using resource_cleanup
   with addClassResourceCleanup instead.
2. Remove instance variables which are only used for resource_cleanup,
   including:
       cls.networks
       cls.floating_ips
       cls.metering_labels
       cls.metering_label_rules

Change-Id: I912a9810a4e22a2cba3a28faeabd70797bbe4ea7

destination, if the source or destination instance location are

so that we allow a different destination to be used.

commit_message:
propagate OSError to MigrationPreCheckError

OSError will lead instance to ERROR state, change to
MigrationPreCheckError will make the instance status not changed.

Also, modify some test cases to make unit test easier

Closes-Bug: 1694636

Change-Id: I3286c32ca205ffd2d5d1aaab88cc96699476e410

filter out the manager and info section

driver.

commit_message:
Install system certs in snap accessible location

Ensure that updated system ca-certificates.crt file is copied into
a location within SNAP_COMMON so that snap based services can
use private CA certs.

Change-Id: Ie948a239e962ce9fdfc868b1741dcccb0711afb8
Related-Bug: 1724012

commit_message:
Remove references to the current task from task() in package_update.yaml

When using the task() expression function within a mistral task the name
is only needed when referncing a different task. These were found with
the mistral-lint PyPI package.

Change-Id: I5ced18cb091db5880837908c600e032e8b312865

commit_message:
Remove references to the current task from task() in plan_management.yaml

When using the task() expression function within a mistral task the name
is only needed when referncing a different task. These were found with
the mistral-lint PyPI package.

Change-Id: I3401a7c5e36a4bf200a4dacb14a44eec04495fc8

commit_message:
Update devstack/README.rst

       * Horizon is enabled by default, so there is no need to enable it.
       * The Gnocchi plugin should be enabled
       * The CloudKitty services need to be enabled

Change-Id: I2b0bac8c8c62479a4701f66efc2703e12ecbaaa3

commit_message:
Fix stand alone haproxy

When deploying a cloud with a stand alone HAProxy server the
nova console port variables are not available to the haproxy
configuration template. This change relocates the variables
from nova_all to the all/nova.yml so that these variables are
globally available to all services that may need access to
them.

Change-Id: Ieee421212ee421e0de69b27daab304cfff5d10ab
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Support for Satellite Capsule in rhel-registration

For deployments running on RHEL with Satellite 6 (or beyond) with
Capsule (Katello API enabled), the Katello API is available
on 8443 port, so the previous API ping didn't work for this case.

Capsule is now supported since we just check if katello-ca-consumer-latest
rpm is available to tell that Satellite version is 6 or beyond.

Closes-Bug: #1716777
Change-Id: If76763b367917fc15f609ad144679750602826eb
(cherry picked from commit ad3ea5bb7a2ee2cb1ae6b1d21b2f0b5a177c9fc6)

commit_message:
Set notification_bind on zaqar websocket

Don't let zaqar websocket listen to notifications on all interfaces:
otherwise, it uses the hostname as a subscription target, and it doesn't
work when the host is set as an IPv6 host. Ultimately this should be
fixed in Zaqar, but this will work around it for now.

Change-Id: I78e0671024b93ec64740cd7a8cda227a5145b789
Related-Bug: #1727406

[{'created': '2017-10-25 17:50:50.000000000', 'message': "db_file passed to broker should not affect it's sharding state

Previously if a ContainerBroker was constructed with
db_file=<hash>_shard.db then the broker would be in state 'SHARDED'
regardless of the presence of a <hash>.db file or not.

This seems like a bad thing, and manifests as a bug when we pass a
sharding container's db_file to the _replicate_object method. The
db_file is <hash>_shard.db (because the container is sharding). The
_replicate_object method uses this to construct a broker instance
which erroneously takes on state sharded.

If _replicate_object ends up using rsync then in _rsync_db it calls
broker.get_brokers() in order to build a list of db files to be
rsync'd, but get_brokers() only returns one broker (for the shard db)
because the broker thinks it is in state sharded. Consequently only
the shard db is rsync'd whereas both dbs should be rsync'd.

This patch decouples the sharding state from the db file passed
to the broker __init__.

commit_message:
db_file passed to broker should not affect it's sharding state

Previously if a ContainerBroker was constructed with
db_file=<hash>_shard.db then the broker would be in state 'SHARDED'
regardless of the presence of a <hash>.db file or not.

This seems like a bad thing, and manifests as a bug when we pass a
sharding container's db_file to the _replicate_object method. The
db_file is <hash>_shard.db (because the container is sharding). The
_replicate_object method uses this to construct a broker instance
which erroneously takes on state sharded.

If _replicate_object ends up using rsync then in _rsync_db it calls
broker.get_brokers() in order to build a list of db files to be
rsync'd, but get_brokers() only returns one broker (for the shard db)
because the broker thinks it is in state sharded. Consequently only
the shard db is rsync'd whereas both dbs should be rsync'd.

This patch decouples the sharding state from the db file passed
to the broker __init__.

Change-Id: Id63d967277ec1634008cc9ce13cefd731836e02c

commit_message:
Fix issue creating NGT using dashboard

Since Django 1.10 a new property DATA_UPLOAD_MAX_NUMBER_FIELDS causes some
plugins to fail during NGT creation. This patch adds a file to override
this property for sahara dashboard.

Depends-On: Id4d15b8bd5f032ff457395af5d77b255b6077a2a
Change-Id: I29ec88d7c733d4a977867dc24e13eb8e98fbcc48
Closes-bug: #1714575
Co-Authored-By: ArchiFleKs <lefevre.kevin@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Create short lived ssh key for enable-ssh-admin.sh

Instead of using the key provided by user on the command line, create
a new short-lived key, give it to Mistral to create a tripleo-admin
user with it, and remove the short-lived key.

Co-Authored-By: John Fulton <fulton@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I6e6ed83fa62319d59d7289b16a1412a340ea6b26
Closes-Bug: #1724578
(cherry picked from commit b0e72c1413c9441aa592b56583e87715e7096152)

commit_message:
WIP: only allow TLS v1.2 in nova servers

The change is localized to nova only, but it will affect all
servers created by nova and *require* that they use TLSv1_2.
They will not be able to use TLSv1_1.  This will require that
clients use TLSv1_2 as well, so may have ramifications.

It is also not an elegant fix, because the protocol to use really
ought to be specifiable via configuration variable on nova.conf,
but currently there is no such parameter.

detailed info and question in:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-April/115776.html

Change-Id: I8ff98bf25849b60ed8ef00c1b9cc969157aa9450

commit_message:
Use addClassResourceCleanup in volume base

This is to use addClassResourceCleanup in volume base to
cleanup volumes and snapshots, so to remove resource_setup
and clear_volumes/clear_snapshots.

Change-Id: I8a609b24bfe3bd3389ec67b45f2442b2d7b648b7

commit_message:
Optimize zuul v3 jobs

- move check container failure from post.yml to run.yml
- add binary related jobs
- use static kolla-ansible src dir, which is helpful for kolla project
  to use.
- generate correct /etc/hosts by using private ip address and hostname
- fix the wrong api interface in global.yml file

Change-Id: Idfdee6dfe18f0fa2d4f984df59b57553122ce298

[{'created': '2017-10-25 13:23:15.000000000', 'message': 'Fix up the imports on a recent change to follow coding spec

Essentially, we want to avoid doing:

    from module import f1, f2, f2

and instead doL

    import module

    module.f1()

This helps with reading the code and understanding where the functions
come from.

commit_message:
Fix up the imports on a recent change to follow coding spec

Essentially, we want to avoid doing:

    from module import f1, f2, f2

and instead doL

    import module

    module.f1()

This helps with reading the code and understanding where the functions
come from.

Change-Id: I1bc06441dc5595e8a0c84a5b5c3db5d88b68a4f2

subject: Display alarm counts in horizon navbar
messages:
[{'account_id': 26438, 'date': '2017-10-16 19:25:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 19159, 'date': '2017-10-19 11:47:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi, what should I do to make the alarm banner appear in the dashboard? I took your changes but I don't see the banner."}, {'account_id': 26438, 'date': '2017-10-20 00:31:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Ifat,  You will need to re-copy the _4020 enabled file to horizon's enabled folder, as well make sure you have recently pulled horizon (the change was only merged last Friday).  Then restart horizon"}, {'account_id': 19159, 'date': '2017-10-22 10:56:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Looks good! Two comments:

- The order of the alarms in the banner is: S,C,W. But Critical is worse then severe, so I think it should be C,S,W

- I'm not sure it's easy to understand what these letters stand for. Why not just write critical/sever/warning (optionally as a tooltip)?"}, {'account_id': 26438, 'date': '2017-10-23 15:10:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 26438, 'date': '2017-10-23 15:14:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Good catch, I've changed the order.
I used only letters to try and make it more compact, I've added tooltips to clarify, if you think it's better to have the full words in the banner I'll change it to that"}, {'account_id': 19134, 'date': '2017-10-24 07:59:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 19140, 'date': '2017-10-24 09:25:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Hi Tyler,
Thanks for your coding, it looks great !
I talked with Ifat & Eyal,
I think we need small changes before merging:
1. it will be better to write the full word of the alarm type, ex: 'CRITICAL'
2. Add a Caption 'Alarms' before the 3 types of Alarms, so it will look like:
Alarms: CRITICAL X   SEVERE Y    WARNING Z
3. Add a border for this section: CRITICAL X   SEVERE Y   WARNING Z
So it will look like it embedded/embossed in the top bar
for example:
https://tympanus.net/Tutorials/BasicReadyToUseCSSStyles/
https://churchm.ag/beveled-pressed-shadow-css-borders/
4. Keep the alarm counters in a badge - just as you did

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 26438, 'date': '2017-10-24 15:46:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 26438, 'date': '2017-10-24 15:47:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the feedback, I've made the requested changes"}, {'account_id': 19140, 'date': '2017-10-25 12:44:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Hi Tyler,
We installed it and need some small CSS changes:

1. Remove the word "Alarms:"
2. Remove all ":" from the alarm types
3. Update .badge class with these properties:
    padding:\xa03px 15px;
    margin-right:\xa018px;
4. The border in the right side is open, please check why it's open'}, {'account_id': 26438, 'date': '2017-10-25 19:37:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 26438, 'date': '2017-10-25 19:40:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Here's how it looks with the latest changes: https://imgur.com/a/8ShqF"}, {'account_id': 19140, 'date': '2017-10-26 07:04:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2

Great Work !
Thanks :)'}]

commit_message:
Display alarm counts in horizon navbar

-This commit makes use of the new extensible header functionality
 in horizon to display the current alarm counts
-When the header is clicked the user is redirected to the alarms
 panel.  If the user is in the admin dashboard they will be sent
 to the admin's alarm panel

Change-Id: Iff6b3b8d7f2efe4107ff3c0639b115f99552e257
Implements: blueprint alarm-header
Signed-off-by: Tyler Smith <tyler.smith@windriver.com>

commit_message:
Add method to compute a file's checksum to fileutils

File checksums are used in projects like glance and
glance_store to verify image uploads and so on, so a
generic oslo utility method could be useful.

Change-Id: I1b76ee1876771e7965fd5704ab6281318f36e810

commit_message:
Fix ocf maas_dns defaults

Though the metadata has a default setting for cfg_dir, the ocf script
did not have the OCF_RESKEY_cfg_dir variable populated. Other ocf
resource scripts set defaults early. This change mimics that
solution.

Change-Id: I4ceb99b45a284a6ba25fb5b5b6372145917ca444

Revisit the process on how RFEs are handled

Tweak the wording so that it's a bit more clear on how to
handle rfe-approved RFEs and why certain RFEs are marked
as 'rfe-postponed'.

commit_message:
add explicit release types for neutron and horizon plugins

Be explicit about the projects that need special release jobs so we
know they are configured correctly.

See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-October/123926.html
for more details.

Change-Id: I73307fb3233c128c8f878da89c1e850831135bc3
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Revise deploy process documentation

Add more details about the node deployment process, when an instance
is booted by nova. This change covers iscsi and direct deploy methods
with PXE boot. This change also updates the sequence diagrams for
deploy process.

Co-Authored-By: Galyna Zholtkevych <galynazholtkevych1991@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Icaec14d10e702627bab0763e40efa77131564dec

commit_message:
Add rsyslog image

This adds a basic rsyslog image with TLS support. For CentOS, we need to
specify the addition of the log normalizer and json parsing modules;
this is not necessary for debian based systems as they're part of the
base rsyslog package.

Change-Id: Ic40cbdaa182fa664c2329e0336259566307165d4

commit_message:
Provide a quick workaround for 1727454

Tripleo-common provides an overcloudrc and an overcloudrc.v3 by default.
Problem is that Keystone v2 API was removed in Queens, so we can't rely
on overcloudrc file anymore.

Until we fix that in tripleo-common, let's source the overcloudrc.v3
after Pike, so we can promote to Queens.

This is technical debt that will be cleaned asap.

Change-Id: If795dfe6953dd7a68bbf075f476f8687c06420a1
Related-Bug: #1727454

First, you should be setting USE_SCREEN=False in local.conf to get reliable process handling.  Second, unstack/stack is the only supported way to restart the services.

Have you looked in $TOP_DIR/.stackenv?  It contains the ENABLED_SERVCES value used for the last stack.sh run, as well as a number of other variables used.  We can add things here for the resulting state from the last stack.sh run as needed, this would be a much more appropriate way to get information on the current running stack than using something intended for other purposes.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-04-20 22:02:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

@Dean: Screen presents tremendous value in debugging and restarting services.  While stackenv gives the list of services, it does not provide the restart information as to what config files were specified to start the services. 

As to unstack/stack being the only way to restart services, this defeats the purpose where snapshots are used instead of repeatedly running unstack/stack. For instance once the system is up and running, we take a snapshot and save it and we can revert to it anytime - but, with this patch we loose that capability - this forces us to run unstack/stack in order to bring the systems back on-line. 
If you look at the statistics from all third party CIs 50+% failures are attributed to the failures of stack.sh. Using snapshot instead of running unstack/stack every time makes the systems reliable as well as saves tons of time, as unstack/stack is very expensive operation. 

Moreover, this requires many vendors to go back and change their scripts - a tremendous resource consumption for no obvious gain. 

I hope you will be sensitive to such constraints.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-03-03 03:00:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2017-10-26 03:52:43.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

Remove screenrc creation

Clean up after the removal of rejoin-stack.sh following merge of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/291453/ (I2f61bb69cc110468a91dcaa4ee7653ede7048467)

* do not create $SCREEN_NAME-screenrc

commit_message:
Use ANSIBLE_HOST_KEY_CHECKING var instead of ssh-common-args

ssh-common-args get ignored in ansible 2.4 due to
https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/30720
This change adds the use of ANSIBLE_HOST_KEY_CHECKING env var as
a replacement for the ssh-common-args cli option.

Closes-bug: 1725224

Change-Id: I398e93d57f6155b59c3f049558558b3a18f4762c
(cherry picked from commit 87235537f791b99ba54a2d6ffd5c4d595e6d47c0)

[{'created': '2017-10-25 15:48:38.000000000', 'message': "shim l3 extensions with neutron-lib

Commit I81748aa0e48b1275df3e1ea41b1d36a117d0097d added the l3 extension
API definition to neutron-lib and commit
I2324a3a02789c798248cab41c278a2d9981d24be rehomed the l3 exceptions.
While we'd like to just consume the changes in neutron, many consumers
use the l3 extension [1] and have branching code that depends on
checking the l3 exceptions. Therefore we can't switch consumers over
using a one-step approach as they will be branching off lib exceptions
while neutron is raising it's own exceptions.

This patch shims the neutron l3 exceptions to ref neutron-lib's. This
will allow us to move consumers over to the l3 code in lib and then
finally consume the l3 changes in lib (removing the shims as well).

[1] http://codesearch.openstack.org/?q=from%20neutron.extensions%20import%20l3

commit_message:
shim l3 exceptions with neutron-lib

Commit I81748aa0e48b1275df3e1ea41b1d36a117d0097d added the l3 extension
API definition to neutron-lib and commit
I2324a3a02789c798248cab41c278a2d9981d24be rehomed the l3 exceptions.
While we'd like to just consume the changes in neutron, many consumers
use the l3 extension [1] and have branching code that depends on
checking the l3 exceptions. Therefore we can't switch consumers over
using a one-step approach as they will be branching off lib exceptions
while neutron is raising it's own exceptions.

This patch shims the neutron l3 exceptions to ref neutron-lib's. This
will allow us to move consumers over to the l3 code in lib and then
finally consume the l3 changes in lib (removing the shims as well).

[1] http://codesearch.openstack.org/?q=from%20neutron.extensions%20import%20l3

Change-Id: Ifd79eb1a92853e49bd4ef028e7a7bd89811c6957

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-21 19:04:08.000000000', 'message': "Partially clarify federation auth plugins

Federation protocols in keystone are very confusing due to the way they
have evolved since the original service provider implementation where
the auth plugin was defined in saml2.py. We renamed saml2.py to
mapped.py[1] and now we can effectively support any federation protocol
as long as there is some kind of Apache module that can understand it
and pass certain IdP and user attributes through to keystone. So we
started recommending not using the 'saml2' auth plugin and instead using
the 'mapped' plugin, eventually removing the the notice when we removed
the plugin[2]. Since the name of the federation protocol resource
created in keystone must match one of the [auth]/methods, we also
changed the documentation to start creating the 'mapped' protocol and
use 'mapped' in the Apache settings[3]. This was really the wrong
course. 'mapped' is not a protocol. Using only 'mapped' prevents us from
defining multiple remote_id_attributes for different protocols.

This patch changes references to the 'mapped' protocol and 'mapped'
plugin back to 'saml2' (we never changed the openid ones).  While the
saml2 plugin does not itself exist, it is defined as an entrypoint to
the mapped plugin, so it all works out. This doesn't solve the problem
for if we want to define different remote_id_attributes for different
SAML2.0 implementations, but there is a workaround for that[4]. Using
'saml2' as the protocol name is just much more intuitive than 'mapped'.

[1] https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/keystone-specs/tree/specs/keystone/juno/generic-mapping-federation.rst
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/397456/
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/371210/
[4] https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1724645/comments/1

commit_message:
Partially clarify federation auth plugins

Federation protocols in keystone are very confusing due to the way they
have evolved since the original service provider implementation where
the auth plugin was defined in saml2.py. We renamed saml2.py to
mapped.py[1] and now we can effectively support any federation protocol
as long as there is some kind of Apache module that can understand it
and pass certain IdP and user attributes through to keystone. So we
started recommending not using the 'saml2' auth plugin and instead using
the 'mapped' plugin, eventually removing the the notice when we removed
the plugin[2]. Since the name of the federation protocol resource
created in keystone must match one of the [auth]/methods, we also
changed the documentation to start creating the 'mapped' protocol and
use 'mapped' in the Apache settings[3]. This was really the wrong
course. 'mapped' is not a protocol. Using only 'mapped' prevents us from
defining multiple remote_id_attributes for different protocols.

This patch changes references to the 'mapped' protocol and 'mapped'
plugin back to 'saml2' (we never changed the openid ones). While the
saml2 plugin does not itself exist, it is defined as an entrypoint to
the mapped plugin, so it all works out. This doesn't solve the problem
for if we want to define different remote_id_attributes for different
SAML2.0 implementations, but there is a workaround for that[4]. Using
'saml2' as the protocol name is just much more intuitive than 'mapped'.

[1] https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/keystone-specs/tree/specs/keystone/juno/generic-mapping-federation.rst
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/397456/
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/371210/
[4] https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1724645/comments/1

Change-Id: I23fc3f1f651c12c4e3c1987dc71008e6e97b4ed8
Related-bug: #1724645

commit_message:
Refactor of _check_tenant_network_connectivity

This is to make the following changes of _check_tenant_network_
connectivity:
1. remove the leading underscore in opencos_base._check_tenant_
   network_connectivity for it's not an internal helper.
2. remove the helper with same name _check_tenant_network_
   connectivity in TestNetworkBasicOps, which unnecessary adds
   the hierachy depth.

John, I'll say the same thing I said in the stable/ocata backport:

"I realize this is removing config options in a stable branch, which we generally don't allow, but these are completely unused and their presence, along with the fact that placement is required in ocata, is actually confusing deployers so IMO we should remove them to avoid confusion until this is actually something we support."'}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2017-10-25 04:55:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

This is a strange case.  The config options aren't used and removing them wont break users that have already deployed and set those options, though I'm not sure why that'd have done that?

Based on the conversation on IRC[1] there is confusion from deployers about needing these options (or not).  Landing this in newton means that deployers that are trying to fast forward through newton don't implement something poorly that then isn't used in ocata+

commit_message:
Remove unused placement_database config options

The placement_database config options were added in Newton
but the actual code to use the options was reverted and is
not used. The help text actually has a typo (Ocata was 15.0.0,
not 14.0.0) and, more importantly, the help text makes it sound
like you should really be setting up a separate database for the
placement service but we don't actually use these options, we use
the api_database options for all of the placement data models.

To avoid confusion until this is actually supported, let's just
remove the options which should have been cleaned up as part of
39fb302fd9c8fc57d3e4bea1c60a02ad5067163f anyway.

Conflicts:
      nova/conf/database.py

NOTE(mriedem): The conflict was due to change
I4cd84f1750ed7cf6c595cec6d6f52b79c73c311b not being in Newton.

Change-Id: I31293ac4689630e4113588ab2c6373cf572b8f38
Closes-Bug: #1670419
(cherry picked from commit 7439e9473617a871c032107ab85b1b623369975f)
(cherry picked from commit 9b695d494444289d82a01547fd56ad8f9a50eab5)

commit_message:
VGPU: Define vgpu resource class

This patch is to add definition of resource class for VGPU and
VGPU_DISPLAY_HEAD, and there will be a series of patches to implement
the whole vgpu feature.

Partially Implements: blueprint add-support-for-vgpu

Change-Id: Ie363453eb9856b39e4ededc5e76807b3d165a1c5

commit_message:
Fix prechecks fail with docker not in deployment host

This changes only evaluates baremetal host group
to look for docker versions.

Change-Id: I64a7314b332958d003f88a00aa73ba79a760a051
Closes-Bug: #1700986

commit_message:
our undercloud default nic should be eth1

In commit 2ffc62209bf14b7eb1c8191a8ef65e6b037c9604 (Don't hardcode eth1
for undercloud nic config) we removed the hard coded nic and instead
rely on the default value from the NeutronPublicInterface heat parameter.
As NeutronPublicInterface defaults to nic1 in overcloud.j2.yaml this
functionally broke the undercloud defaults as we typically expect eth1
to be the bridged interface used for the control_plane network traffic.

This patch sets the correct default again by setting the value
manually in the undercloud heat environment.

NOTE: using eth1 per the old hard coded value. Eventually we want
this to be nic2 but there has been a regression in os-net-config
which is causing "active nics" not to be detected correctly in
all cases.

Change-Id: Idb1e34bd3dff7c6412082ab4201f8e6af35a939d
Closes-bug: #1721853

Use upgrade rather than create_schema for wather database

watcher has moved to version control. upgrade should be used rather than
create_schema

commit_message:
Remove the duplication of the inventory

Use folder as inventory, which could remove the duplicated parent
and children groups in all-in-one and multinode

Change-Id: I62e67569bf1aee76f91e5740be52c778a9faf982

commit_message:
Import the config drive docs from openstack-manuals

As part of the docs migration from openstack-manuals to
nova in the pike release we missed the config-drive docs.

This change does the following:

1. Imports the config-drive doc into the user guide.
2. Fixes a broken link to the metadata service in the doc.
3. Removes a note about liberty being the current release.
4. Adds a link in the API reference parameters to actually
   point at the document we have in tree now, which is
   otherwise not very discoverable as the main index does
   not link to this page (or the user index for that matter).

Partial-Bug: #1714017
Closes-Bug: #1720873

Change-Id: I1d54e1f5a1a94e9821efad99b7fa430bd8fece0a

commit_message:
Require python-openstackclient 3.11.0

Updating python-tripleoclient in pike causes a bug
at the time of issuing non-authorized commands
like openstack [undercloud|overcloud|help...].
This bug was solved in python-openstackclient
commit Ifdf65f3bb90fb923947a2cbe80a881d71a3fee56
which is present in version 3.10.0.

Added 3.11.0 in global- requirement as 3.10.0
version was blocked due to failures in CI [1]

[1] https://github.com/openstack/requirements/
commit/cfdf9612cf32608768e9b3c4983bfaf896d46e62

Change-Id: I12b39279e5d663837ed70f70462e56b36d38e9ac
Related-Bug: #1717524

commit_message:
Fix to use . to source script files

Adhering to coding conventions. Refer to ``Code conventions`` at [1] for details.
When you have to source a script file, for example, a credentials file to gain access
to user-only or admin-only CLI commands, use . instead of source.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/contributor-guide/writing-style/code-conventions.html

Change-Id: I28cf540fab397ef4a9b7f458d2bdaaecc9e543cb

[{'created': '2017-10-25 16:59:18.000000000', 'message': "add neutron release notes job template to vmware-nsx

The vmware-nsx release notes job is failing to build release notes that
used to build fine. It appears vmware-nsx is getting a very old version
of reno [1], which I suspect maybe the cause here. Neutron's release
notes job uses a much newer version [2].

This patch adds the release-notes-jobs-neutron template to the
vmware-nsx project as I suspect it will address the issue described
above.

[1] http://logs.openstack.org/10/513510/11/check/build-openstack-releasenotes/9487aeb/job-output.txt.gz#_2017-10-25_15_39_29_327289
[2] http://logs.openstack.org/83/511983/11/check/build-openstack-releasenotes/4b0910a/job-output.txt.gz#_2017-10-24_19_01_58_446340

Change-Id: I7d95a88f0cd94ae11ab15497278c737423203e45
"}, {'created': '2017-10-25 17:30:33.000000000', 'message': 'remove release notes jobs from vmware-nsx

This patch removes the release notes job from the vmware-nsx pipeline.
The vmware-nsx release notes have some syntax errors; it appears they
were never built in v2 jobs. Therefore we can add this job back in
when/if they are fixed up in vmware-nsx.

Change-Id: I7d95a88f0cd94ae11ab15497278c737423203e45
'}]
commit_message:
remove release notes jobs from vmware-nsx

This patch removes the release notes job from the vmware-nsx pipeline.
The vmware-nsx release notes have some syntax errors; it appears they
were never built in v2 jobs. Therefore we can add this job back in
when/if they are fixed up in vmware-nsx.

Change-Id: I7d95a88f0cd94ae11ab15497278c737423203e45

commit_message:
Fix to return 'root_uuid' as part of command status

IPA does not return 'root_uuid' as part of command status when
provisioning of whole disk image is done using 'agent' deploy
interface from ironic. This commit fixes the issue.
Also updated Dockerfile to include package 'bsdmainutils' related
to 'hexdump' binary.

Change-Id: I89597fe4a704686fe31c064c3443fd8404a300e5
Partial-Bug: #1713916

commit_message:
Update tiny-instance image to contain branch name

With this patch branch is added to tiny-instance image name.

Also fixed a problem with BRANCH_PATH was set to refs/heads/master
after migration to zuulv3

Change-Id: I490e2d51a7c3fbc2cc0fa78a95b984874ab934f7

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-09-12 21:58:21.000000000', 'message': 'WIP Action for the UI to prepare container image parameters

Currently the UI cannot deploy with containers because the mandatory
container parameters are not set. This change adds an action in the
create_deployment_plan and update_deployment_plan workflows which does
a container prepare with the default options.

By default this action does nothing, so the CLI is not affected. The
UI will need to invoke these workflows with
container_images_prepare=true to trigger the prepare action.

In the future the UI can prompt for parameters to allow more complex
scenarios such as a local registry.

Marked as WIP until there are unit tests.

Change-Id: Ibce7658468c1b3689a7481deb94dd43e1f3ead52
Closes-Bug: #1716778

'}, {'created': '2017-10-02 21:12:14.000000000', 'message': 'Action to always populate container image parameters

Currently the UI cannot deploy with containers because the mandatory
container parameters are not set. Also a CLI will not deploy unless
passed an environment generated by the "images prepare" call.

This change adds an action in the create_deployment_plan and
update_deployment_plan workflows which does a container prepare with
the default options, so that the mandatory image parameters are always
populated with values which will work.

commit_message:
Action to always populate container image parameters

Currently the UI cannot deploy with containers because the mandatory
container parameters are not set. Also a CLI will not deploy unless
passed an environment generated by the "images prepare" call.

This change adds an action in the create_deployment_plan and
update_deployment_plan workflows which does a container prepare with
the default options, so that the mandatory image parameters are always
populated with values which will work.

Change-Id: Ibce7658468c1b3689a7481deb94dd43e1f3ead52
Closes-Bug: #1716778
